  "articleSummary": "This article is a practical tutorial for developers self-hosting Docker services on home networks or VPS providers (e.g., Vultr, AWS). Its core thesis is that security is entirely the user’s responsibility when self-hosting, covering image update strategies (pinning vs. `:latest`), secrets management (never hard-code, use tools like Docker secrets or `.env`), and additional techniques like canary tokens, network segmentation, and authenticated proxies. The tone is instructive and slightly humorous (e.g., “Yolo, avoid if possible”), using emoji headers and a “For the brave” framing to emphasize the DIY security burden. Key recommendations include using Dependabot/Renovate for updates, generating strong secrets, and validating placeholders to prevent unsafe defaults.",
